li.p:
 Using , indicate the
	vectors \xvec such that



 \coords{\xvec}{\bcal} = \twovec{2}{-1}



 \coords{\xvec}{\bcal} = \twovec{-1}{-2}



 \coords{\xvec}{\bcal} = \twovec{0}{3}

Form the matrix
P_{\bcal} = \left[\begin{array}{rrrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{array}\right]\text{,}
which shows that the vectors are linearly independent and span \real^4.

Looking at the reduced row echelon form, we find
\left[\begin{array}{rrrrr} \vvec_1 \amp \vvec_2 \amp \vvec_3 \amp \vvec_4 \amp \vvec_5 \\ \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrrrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp - 2 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}
This shows that the vectors are not linearly independent since there is not a pivot position in every column. Therefore, the set of vectors does not form a basis for \real^3. Of course, we also know this because a set of vectors for \real^3 must contain exactly three vectors.

statement.p:
	Suppose that we have the vectors

	\vvec_1=\threevec{1}{1}{1},
	\vvec_2=\threevec{\cos\left(\frac\pi6\right)}
	{\cos\left(\frac{3\pi}6\right)}
	{\cos\left(\frac{5\pi}6\right)}
	\vvec_3=\threevec{\cos\left(\frac{2\pi}6\right)}
	{\cos\left(\frac{6\pi}6\right)}
	{\cos\left(\frac{10\pi}6\right)}
      .



 Explain why \bcal=\{\vvec_1,\vvec_2,\vvec_3\}
	is a basis for \real^3.  Notice that you may enter
	\cos\left(\frac\pi6\right) into Sage as
	cos(pi/6). 








 If \xvec=\threevec{15}{15}{15}, find
	\coords{\xvec}{\bcal}. 



 Find the matrices P_{\bcal} and
	P_{\bcal}^{-1}.  If
	\xvec=\threevec{x_1}{x_2}{x_3} and
	\coords{\xvec}{\bcal} = \threevec{c_1}{c_2}{c_3},
	explain why c_1 is the average of x_1,
	x_2, and x_3.

li.p:
We have
P_{\bcal}= \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \amp \frac{1}{2} \\ 1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \amp \frac{1}{2} \end{array}\right],~~~ P_{\bcal}^{-1}= \left[\begin{array}{rrr} \frac{1}{3} \amp \frac{1}{3} \amp \frac{1}{3} \\ \frac{\sqrt{3}}{3} \amp 0 \amp -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{3} \\ \frac{1}{3} \amp -\frac{2}{3} \amp \frac{1}{3} \end{array}\right]\text{.}
Since we have \coords{\xvec}{\bcal}=C_{\bcal}^{-1}\xvec, we have c_1=\frac13 x_1 + \frac13 x_2 + \frac13 x_3 = \frac13(x_1+x_2+x_3) .
